body:
@jtattermusch I have started this research recently to ensure that in google/protobuf#3431 I can handle gRPC requirements you have mentioned earlier correctly. From what I have learned, in current preview version, Project Bedrock is temporarily tied to the SignalR Core - so it's definitely not ready to be used for gRPC purposes. AFAIK the target for .NET Core 2.2 is to provide a proper HTTP/2 abstraction.

I will be monitoring the progress on the .NET Core/Project Bedrock side and I will be happy to create a PoC as soon as it will be feasible using the preview versions. I would really like to handle this scenario correctly.

From my perspective HTTP/2 bi-directional streaming is a must have here. Do you have any other specific features in mind that I should be monitoring?

I have not uploaded it yet. I will try to put it together tomorrow. My current super-early-prototype looks like this:

```
                var httpStream = (Http2Stream)context.Features;
                var ct = CancellationToken.None;
                var pipeReader = httpStream.RequestBodyPipe.Reader;

                httpStream.Output.WriteResponseHeaders(200, null, new HttpResponseHeaders
                {
                    HeaderContentType = "application/grpc",
                    HeaderTrailer = "grpc-status"
                });
                while (true)
                {
                    var (isCompressed, message) = await ReadLengthDelimitedMessageOrEos(pipeReader, ct);
                    if (message == null)
                    {
                        var trailers = new HttpResponseHeaders();
                        trailers.Append("grpc-status", "0");
                        httpStream.Output.WriteResponseHeaders(200, null, trailers);
                        await httpStream.Output.WriteStreamSuffixAsync();

                        pipeReader.Complete();
                        break;
                    }
                    else
                    {
                        var lengthDelimitedPrefix = new byte[5];
                        BinaryPrimitives.WriteUInt32BigEndian(lengthDelimitedPrefix.AsSpan(1), (uint)message.Value.Length);
                        await httpStream.Output.WriteDataAsync(lengthDelimitedPrefix, ct);
                        await httpStream.Output.WriteDataAsync(message.Value.ToSpan(), ct);

                        pipeReader.AdvanceTo(message.Value.End);
                    }
                }
```

It is echoing the original message back to the client and it is succesfully processed by the Greeter client. I have not validated it with Wireshark yet.

The problem I am experiencing currently is that it works with `Grpc.Core.Client` buf fails with `WinHttpHandler`-based client. Removing line
```
httpStream.Output.WriteResponseHeaders(200, null, trailers);
```

fixes the error, but I am not sure where the true problem really is (if this is problem with trailers or what).

BTW. According to rfc7540
> Pseudo-header fields MUST NOT appear in trailers

> The HEADERS frame starting the trailers header block has the
   END_STREAM flag set.

So this is likely a problem and I think that the best place to add trailers implementation is: `WriteStreamSuffixAsync`
